rban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Rose de Beauville was born about 1214. She had at least 1 daughter with William FitzRichard. She died on 4 April 1291, in Cornwall, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 78."},"et":{"Abt 1214–4 April 1291":"umbes 1214–4. aprill 1291","1205–1265":"1205–1265","1230–1325":"1230–1325","1214–1291":"1214–1291","Abt 1230":"umbes 1230","1205":"1205","1325":"1325","1214":"1214","4 April 1291":"4. aprill 1291","1265":"1265","1230":"1230","Abt 1214":"umbes 1214","1291":"1291","Cornwall, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall